y0": 0.47, "x1": 19.47, "y1": 12.7}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 53.58, "x1": 63.04, "y1": 76.83}, {"x0": 64.97, "y0": 31.96, "x1": 90.63, "y1": 52.22}, {"x0": 64.85, "y0": 55.32, "x1": 91.56, "y1": 73.44}], "full_text": "Lecture\nGastrointestinal system\nRadiology\n7\nImaging modalities of GIT pathologies:\n1. X-ray.\n2. Barium studies.\n3. Ultrasound.\n4. Computed tomography (CT).\n5. Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)\nPlain X-ray\nAlthough abdominal radiography has lower sensitivity\nand specificity than a CT of the abdomen, it still has\ncertain uses, like:\n1. A preliminary evaluation of bowel gas in an\nemergent setting like Multiple air fluid levels (in\nintestinal obstruction).\n2. Evaluation of radiopaque tubes and lines.\n3. Evaluation for radiopaque foreign bodies.\n4. Evaluation for presence of free gas (Air under\ndiaphragm in hollow organ perforation).\nMultiple air fluid levels\nAir under diaphragm\nBarium studies\n1. Barium swallow: (for evaluation of oesophagus)\n2. Barium meal: (evaluation of stomach)\n3. Barium follow through: (for evaluation of small bowel)\n4. Barium enema: (for evaluation of large bowel)\n88"}